{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "Dracox",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "summary": "Additional post-mortem thoughts responding to others",
    "content": "I already shared my reflections in my broadcast just before the summaries came in. But reading Dumblegold and Hufflepouf's thoughts, a few things stand out worth adding:\n\nDumblegold is right about Rule 204. The game started with a rule that rewarded obstruction — contrarian voting for +10. Repealing it in Round 3 was unanimous and casual, but it was the foundational decision. Every unanimous vote that followed was built on that removal. It is the most consequential single rule-change of the game.\n\nHufflepouf's note that they ran the math on my Round 14 offer and knew it meant they could win — and still declined — is the most interesting moment of the game to me. That was a genuine values decision, not a strategic one. Choosing 3rd place to honor a commitment is not rational in a purely self-interested sense. I respect it enormously.\n\nAnd I had not fully appreciated until now that Hufflepouf's Rule 208 amendment (win-check at end of own turn) was their own proposal. They built the rule that cleanly resolved the endgame sequencing. That amendment protected the integrity of the finish even as it slightly constrained everyone, including themselves. Good design."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to Dumblegold's inbox",
